<!-- ═══ Context ═══ -->
<div class="section" id="context" style="margin-top: 40px;">
    <div class="text-block">
        <h2>Context</h2>
    </div>
    <div class="text-block">
        <p class="body-text">Viscovery possessed market-leading AI video recognition technology, but faced enormous challenges in commercializing it. The team's initial instinct was to build a YouTube-like single video platform. However, through in-depth interviews with B2B clients (TV broadcasters, content providers), I uncovered a critical Market Gap:</p>
    </div>
    <div class="image-block">
        <img src="/images/viscovery/vds.webp" alt="Video Discovery System — AI core technology" class="rounded-image">
        <p class="caption">our AI core technology "Video Discovery System"</p>
    </div>
    <div class="text-block">
        <h4 class="phase-label">Scale Mismatch</h4>
    </div>
    <div class="text-block">
        <p class="body-text">B2B clients needed to process hundreds of videos per month — YouTube's "upload one at a time" workflow couldn't support their throughput requirements.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="text-block">
        <h4 class="phase-label">Scenario Conflict</h4>
    </div>
    <div class="text-block">
        <p class="body-text">The sales team needed "firepower demos," the content operations team needed "efficient management," and advertisers needed "precise data." Forcing all three into one platform created an experience where each use case undermined the others.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="text-block">
        <h3>My Role</h3>
    </div>
    <div class="text-block">
        <p class="body-text">As the team's sole Product Designer, I collaborated directly with the PM, algorithm team, and sales, owning the full design process from user research, product scoping, and information architecture to UI design. I helped the team shift from a "tech demo mindset" to a "SaaS product mindset" and redefined the product boundaries.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="image-block">
        <img src="/images/viscovery/first-approach.webp" alt="Our first approach to the platform" class="rounded-image">
        <p class="caption">our first approach to the platform</p>
    </div>
</div>

<!-- ═══ Discovery → Strategy ═══ -->
<div class="section" id="discovery">
    <div class="text-block">
        <h2>Discovery → Strategy</h2>
    </div>
    <div class="text-block">
        <p class="body-text">Through in-depth interviews with B2B clients, I mapped out their current workflows, pain points, and unmet needs — and identified three fundamentally different user scenarios that the product needed to serve.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="image-block">
        <img src="/images/viscovery/interview-table.webp" alt="User interview findings" class="rounded-image">
        <p class="caption">We interview with several users to understand their behaviour and highlight the crucial points.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="text-block">
        <h4 class="phase-label">How I Aligned the Team</h4>
    </div>
    <div class="text-block">
        <p class="body-text">This decision didn't face significant internal resistance — the early consensus was that the direction was sound, and we should ship an MVP first, then iterate based on user feedback. My approach to building alignment:</p>
    </div>
    <div class="text-block">
        <h4 class="phase-label">Persona Scenario Comparison</h4>
    </div>
    <div class="text-block">
        <p class="body-text">I laid out the three user scenarios side by side, making it clear that "sales demo" and "daily operations" fundamentally shouldn't coexist in the same interface.</p>
    </div>

    <!-- Persona Cards -->
