    <div class="text-block">
        <h4 class="phase-label">Prototype-Driven Demonstration</h4>
    </div>
    <div class="text-block">
        <p class="body-text">I created prototypes showing the experience gap between the original approach (cramming all features into one platform) and the new approach, letting stakeholders feel the problem firsthand rather than relying on verbal arguments alone.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="text-block">
        <h4 class="phase-label">Dividing Functions into Platforms</h4>
    </div>
    <div class="text-block">
        <p class="body-text">Three scenarios didn't mean three separate products. After evaluating the practical product boundaries, I converged them into two platforms:</p>
    </div>
    <div class="text-block">
        <h4 class="phase-label">Demo Site</h4>
    </div>
    <div class="text-block">
        <p class="body-text">Sales only needed to pull recognition results for external demos, with no need to access video management or ad placement. Keeping it independent ensured a lightweight, focused showcase experience free from back-end complexity.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="text-block">
        <h4 class="phase-label">Operations Platform VidSense + Tag2Ad (Integrating Persona B + C)</h4>
    </div>
    <div class="text-block">
        <p class="body-text">Video recognition management and ad placement appeared to serve different roles, but in practice they overlapped significantly — the same content provider (e.g., a TV broadcaster) typically had both needs. I consolidated these into a single platform with header-based view switching, eliminating the need for users to jump between two separate systems.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="image-block">
        <img src="/images/viscovery/architecture.webp" alt="Platform architecture diagram" style="width:100%;">
    </div>
</div>

<!-- ═══ Core Design Challenges ═══ -->
<div class="section" id="core-challenges">
    <div class="text-block">
        <h2>Core Design Challenges</h2>
    </div>
    <div class="text-block">
        <h4 class="phase-label">Information Architecture Restructure — From YouTube Clone to Ops-First Platform</h4>
    </div>
    <div class="text-block">
        <div class="body-text">
            <p>In the first version, we adopted YouTube's content architecture — centered on the single-video player page. But persona analysis revealed that the content operations team's core need wasn't "watching" — it was "batch management" and "efficient operations."</p>
            <br>
            <p>I deconstructed the first version's information architecture and restructured it as follows:</p>
        </div>
    </div>
    <div class="image-block">
        <div class="ba-slider" id="ia-compare">
            <div class="ba-before">
                <img src="/images/viscovery/before.webp" alt="Before: YouTube-style layout">
                <span class="ba-label ba-label-before">Before</span>
            </div>
            <div class="ba-after">
                <img src="/images/viscovery/after.webp" alt="After: Ops-first platform">
                <span class="ba-label ba-label-after">After</span>
            </div>
            <div class="ba-handle">
                <div class="ba-handle-line"></div>
                <div class="ba-handle-circle">
                    <svg width="24" height="24" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none">
                        <path d="M8 4l-6 8 6 8M16 4l6 8-6 8" stroke="#fff" stroke-width="2.5" stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round"/>
                    </svg>
                </div>
                <div class="ba-handle-line"></div>
            </div>
        </div>
    </div>
    <div class="text-block">
        <div class="body-text">
            <p>Navigation Shift: Moved the focal point from "video playback" to a "folder and batch management" view, enabling operators to quickly locate, filter, and bulk-process hundreds of videos.</p>
            <br>
            <p>Batch Operations First: Converted previously one-at-a-time actions — tag editing, recognition result review — into multi-select batch operations, meeting B2B clients' high-throughput requirements.</p>
            <br>
            <p>Status Visibility: Surfaced each video's recognition status (uploading / processing / complete / failed) directly at the list level, allowing operators to grasp the overall state at a glance without clicking into individual items.</p>
        </div>
    </div>
    <div class="text-block">
        <h4 class="phase-label">Asynchronous UX — Turning System Latency into User Productivity</h4>
    </div>
    <div class="text-block">
        <p class="body-text">The biggest experience killer in AI video recognition was latency. To prevent users from being blocked during bulk uploads, I introduced an Asynchronous Interaction design:</p>
    </div>
    <div class="text-block">
        <h4 class="phase-label">Task Manager Pattern</h4>
    </div>
    <div class="text-block">
        <p class="body-text">I designed a global progress manager. While videos were uploading or undergoing AI processing in the background, users could minimize the window to the bottom-right corner and continue editing tags or organizing folders. This successfully transformed "system processing time" into "productive user work time."</p>
    </div>
    <div class="image-block">
        <video src="/images/viscovery/task_manager.mov" autoplay loop muted playsinline class="rounded-image" style="width:100%;display:block;"></video>
    </div>
    <div class="text-block">
        <h4 class="phase-label">Resilient Error Handling</h4>
    </div>
    <div class="text-block">
        <p class="body-text">For network interruptions or recognition failures, I designed clear "resume upload" and "re-run recognition" entry points, ensuring the automated pipeline wouldn't be completely stalled by a single error.</p>
    </div>
</div>

<!-- ═══ Impact & Learnings ═══ -->
<div class="section" id="impact">
    <div class="text-block">
        <h2>Impact &amp; Learnings</h2>
    </div>
    <div class="text-block">
        <h4 class="phase-label">Commercial Win</h4>
    </div>
    <div class="text-block">
        <p class="body-text">Successfully leveraged this MVP platform architecture to help the company secure its first landmark B2B client (a TV broadcaster), formally validating the commercial viability of the AI tagging technology.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="text-block">
        <h4 class="phase-label">Operational Efficiency</h4>
    </div>
    <div class="text-block">
        <p class="body-text">By redesigning the video tagging workflow, I reduced the steps required to complete a single video's tags from 6 clicks to 4 (a 33% reduction). At the TV broadcaster's operational scale of hundreds of videos per month, this optimization saved operators significant amounts of repetitive work.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="text-block">
        <h4 class="phase-label">Design Ops Improvement</h4>
    </div>
    <div class="text-block">
        <p class="body-text">Facing poor cross-departmental communication efficiency (PM, algorithm team, sales) and version control issues inherent to the Sketch era, I led the team's tooling transformation — migrating from a fragmented file-sharing workflow to Figma-based online collaboration, achieving a "Design as Spec" approach. I drew complete logic jumps and data states directly within design files, enabling algorithm engineers to intuitively understand scenarios like "what to display when recognition confidence drops below 80%," dramatically reducing development misinterpretation and back-and-forth confirmation costs.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="image-block">
        <div class="two-col-images">
            <img src="/images/viscovery/design-spec-1.webp" alt="Design spec with interaction details" class="rounded-image">
            <img src="/images/viscovery/design-spec-2.webp" alt="Full platform screen map" class="rounded-image">
        </div>
        <p class="caption">Each screen is attached with interaction details and combine into a whole picture of the platform</p>
    </div>
</div>

<!-- ═══ Reflection ═══ -->
<div class="section" id="reflection">
    <div class="text-block">
        <h2>Reflection: What I'd Do Differently</h2>
    </div>
    <div class="text-block">
        <p class="body-text">Engage real users earlier. In the early stages of this project, we designed from a completely blank slate — relying on internal team discussions and assumptions to build the first version. It was only after connecting with a TV broadcaster's actual use case through the sales team that we discovered a fundamental gap between our original direction and real client needs, ultimately leading to a complete interface overhaul. If I could do it over, I would proactively leverage the sales team's client channels from the very beginning to directly understand B2B users' real workflows and pain points, rather than waiting until the product was already built to course-correct. This was the most critical lesson from this project: for B2B products, the earlier the designer gains access to end users' real scenarios, the lower the cost of rework down the line.</p>
    </div>
</div>
